'''Yamanashi District''' (山梨郡, やまなしぐん) was a [[district]] in [[Yamanashi Prefecture]] (formerly [[Kai Province]]).

The name of Yamanashi Prefecture originates from Yamanashi District.

== District Area ==
At the time of its dissolution, the district encompassed the following areas, though its boundaries were not administratively defined:

* All of [[Yamanashi City]]
* Most of [[Koshu City]] (excluding Katsunuma Town Kami-Iwasaki, Katsunuma Town Shimo-Iwasaki, Katsunuma Town Fujii, Yamato Town Hikage, Yamato Town Tano, and Yamato Town Tokusa)
* Part of [[Kofu City]] (generally east of the {{ill|Arakawa River (Yamanashi)|ja|荒川 (山梨県)|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, excluding Kurobe Town)
* Part of [[Fuefuki City]] (north of Kasugai Town Komatsu, Kasugai Town Kokufu, Kasugai Town Shizume, Kasugai Town Yamazaki, and Kasugai Town Matsumoto)

In ancient times, the district also included Ichinomiya Town, Misaka Town, and Isawa Town in Fuefuki City.

== Pre-modern History ==
=== Formation and Administrative Divisions of Yamanashi District ===
[[File:Yamanashi-oka shrine №1.jpg|thumb|250px|Yamanashi Oka Shrine]]
[[File:Ruins of a temple of Teramoto in Fuefuki City Yamanashi Pref.jpg|thumb|250px|Ruins of Teramoto Ancient Temple]]
In the {{ill|Wamyo Ruijusho|ja|和名類聚抄|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Yamanashi District was one of the four districts of Kai Province and was pronounced "Yamanashi" (夜萬奈之). It had ten administrative subdistricts (kango), with the first five—Oso, Noro, Hayashibe, Inoe, and Tamanoi—belonging to Yamanashi East District, and the latter five—Isawa, Uwato, Yamanashi, Kami, and Ono—belonging to Yamanashi West District. In the {{ill|Late Kofun period|ja|古墳時代後期|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the area was divided into competing factions, and the boundaries of the district may have reflected this rivalry.

Artifacts and inscriptions bearing the names of these subdistricts have been discovered at archaeological sites, such as {{ill|Onohara Site|ja|大原遺跡|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in Ichinomiya Town and the {{ill|Otsubo Site|ja|大坪遺跡|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in Kofu City.

=== Origins and Etymology of "Yamanashi" ===
The Wamyo Ruijusho spells the name as "Yamanashi" (夜萬奈之) or "Yamanase" (山無瀬). The district name became fixed as "Yamanashi" following an edict in Wado 6 (713) mandating the use of auspicious two-character kanji for place names. Contrary to popular belief that the name derives from an abundance of {{ill|yamanashi trees|ja|ヤマナシ|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (wild pears), it is more likely derived from "Yama narasu" (山ならす), meaning "to level mountains," symbolizing the flat terrain of the eastern Kofu Basin.

The district was a political and cultural center of ancient Kai Province, home to early government offices and Buddhist temples such as the {{ill|Kai Provincial Temple|ja|甲斐国分寺|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. In later centuries, it became a stronghold of the {{ill|Takeda clan|ja|武田氏|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, with their main castle in Kofu City.

